{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17415586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17415586"},"attributes":{"position":56,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T09:10:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T09:10:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17427"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478303"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:12:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:12:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17427"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"17427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17427"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.18,0.19,0.01,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10117"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101172"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10117"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83609"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"8023"},{"type":"tags","id":"8044"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34749"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101172"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy of Chinese descent presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent concerned about multiple dark spots on his face that have been present for the past year. The spots are asymptomatic and have gradually increased in number despite winter. He has unmedicated ADHD, and uses topical corticosteroid occasionally for his eczema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple well-defined, uniformly brown-to-black macules measuring 2-5 mm scattered across his cheeks and nose. The lesions are flat with regular borders. There is no associated inflammation or scaling. There are dry mildly pruritic patches in his flexures with show lichenification.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Caf\u00e9-au-lait macules","Melasma","Naevus of Ota","Melanoma","Lentigines"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is typical of \u003Cstrong\u003Elentigines\u003C/strong\u003E, which are benign hyperpigmented macules which are less than 0.5cm in size, and have regular borders, and uniform brown-to-black colour. They commonly appear in childhood, particularly in fair skinned populations, and tend to increase in number over time on anywhere on the body. Freckles or ephelis in contrast will fade during less sun-exposure times such as winter. The absence of concerning features such as asymmetry, border irregularity or colour variation supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelanoma\u003C/strong\u003E is rare in children and typically presents as a single lesion with concerning features such as asymmetry, irregular borders, colour variation, or rapid growth. The multiple uniform lesions in this case would be highly unusual for melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaevus of Ota\u003C/strong\u003E is a dermal melanocytosis that presents as a unilateral, blue-grey patch in the distribution of the ophthalmic and maxillary branches of the trigeminal nerve. It is usually present at birth or appears in early childhood. The bilateral, discrete macules in this case are not consistent with naevus of Ota.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelasma\u003C/strong\u003E presents as larger patches of symmetrical hyperpigmentation typically on the cheeks, forehead, and upper lip. It is uncommon in children and is more frequently seen in women, often triggered by hormonal changes or sun exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaf\u00e9-au-lait macules\u003C/strong\u003E are light brown patches that are typically larger than lentingines and present from birth or early infancy rather than developing at school-age. Multiple caf\u00e9-au-lait macules can be associated with neurofibromatosis type 1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen multiple lentigines are present, particularly in unusual distributions or in large numbers, consideration should be given to associated syndromes such as LEOPARD syndrome or Peutz-Jeghers syndrome. However, the presentation described here is consistent with benign lentigines requiring no specific treatment beyond sun protection and monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lentigines can be distinguished from melanoma by their small size, regular borders, and uniform colour.","Multiple lentigines may be associated with genetic syndromes and warrant further evaluation."],"references":["Ngan V, Oakley A. Lentigines. DermNet NZ. 2016.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/lentigo","Lodish MB, Stratakis CA. The differential diagnosis of familial lentiginosis syndromes. Fam Cancer. 2011 Sep;10(3):481-90.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3417307/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83609"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17427"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83609"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-30T19:23:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-30T19:24:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10117"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101172"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type"